INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('37', 'Handout - Event Budget Management', '<p>Build budgets based on fixed costs, variable costs per attendee or a combination. Event&rsquo;s budget tool alleviates the pains of tracking funds, recalculating variable costs and monitoring budget room by automatically accounting for the variety of event data affecting the budget. Regardless of the number of attendees, many planners are given a fixed amount of funding. The budget module eliminates the challenges associated with keeping track of expenses and<br>attendance so planners can maximize allocated dollars and still deliver on meeting expectations.</p>', '02', 'Jessica Mackie', '2011-02-11 04:55:08', 'MTI5NzQwMDEwOF93ZWVrXzZfYnVkZ2V0X2FuZF9jb250cm9s.102ppt.pdf', '807', '42', '0', null, '1162', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('38', 'Advances in Hospitality and Leisure', '<p><strong>Overview</strong></p>\r\n<p>Advances in Hospitality and Leisure (AHL), a peer-review series published annually, is seeking to deliver refreshing insights from a host of scientific investigations pertaining to hospitality, leisure, and tourism while rendering an academic forum to stimulate discussion on current literature, contemporary issues and emerging trends essential to theory advancement as well as professional practices from a global perspective.<br>The main focus of the series is to divulge the innovative methods of inquiry so as to inspire new research topics that are vital and have been in large neglected.&nbsp; AHL strives to address the needs of the populace willing to disseminate seminal ideas, concepts, and theories derived from scholarly inquiries. Potential readers may retrieve useful texts helping outline new research agendas, suggest viable topics for a dissertation work, and augment the knowledge of the new subjects of learning.&nbsp; <br>Since the d&eacute;but of the series in 2004, AHL has published in a variety of conceptual and empirical articles contributed by tourism, leisure and hospitality scholars across 14 countries.&nbsp; The themes of those research papers cover a broad range of issues such as consumer behaviors, economic impacts, environmental impact, human resource management, marketing, natural disaster, pricing strategy, product development, risk management, service quality, and terrorism.</p>\r\n<p><strong>About the Author:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Joseph S. Chen is Associate Professor, Recreation, Park, and Tourism Studies Department at Indiana University, Bloomington, USA, and: <br>&nbsp;&bull; Principle Investigator, National Science Foundation Grant<br>&nbsp;&bull; Co-Investigator, Norwegian Research Council Grant<br>&nbsp;&bull; Co-founding chair, International Conference on Hospitality and Leisure Applied Research (I-CHLAR)<br>&nbsp;&bull; Editor-in-Chief, Advances in Hospitality and Leisure<br>&nbsp;&bull; Recipient, W. Bradford Wiley Memorial Research Award<br>&nbsp;&bull; Recipient, The Best Article of the Year Award by the Journal of Hospitality and Tourism Research<br>&nbsp;&bull; U.S. Fulbright Senior Scholar<br><strong><em>Education</em></strong><br>&nbsp;&bull; Ph.D. at Pennsylvania State University, 1996<br>&nbsp;&bull; M.A. at George Washington University, 1986<br>&nbsp;&bull; B.A. at Chinese Culture University, 1982</p>\r\n<p><strong>Table of Contents:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 1.</strong></em> Is the servqual scale an adequate measure of quality in leisure, tourism and hospitality?</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 2.</strong></em> Marketing to lodging, food service and club consumers in the future: a Delphi study to predict marketing management in 20</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 3. </strong></em>Constraints to participation in the arts by the young old, old and oldest old</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 4.</strong></em> An In-depth comparative review of burnout, p;ateau and derailment: concepts that threaten the success of hospitality industry</p>\r\n<p>&bull;<em><strong> Chapter 5</strong></em>. Price-ending practices and consumer behavior in the hospitality industry: a reciprocal phenomenon</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 6.</strong></em> Uses of hospitality and leisure services: voices of visitors with disabilities</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 7</strong></em>. Collaborative supply chain management in the airline sector: the role of global distribution systems</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 8.</strong></em> Measurement issues in leisure research: accuracy, bias and reliability</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 9</strong></em>. The evalution of norwegians&rsquo; trip satisfaction toward southern European destinations</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <strong><em>Chapter 10.</em></strong> Market developments in the hotel sector in eastern central Europe</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 11.</strong></em> Factors influencing German hoteliers&rsquo; attitudes toward environmental management</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 12.</strong></em> An examination of the brand relationship quality scale in the evaluation of restaurant brands</p>\r\n<p>&bull;<em><strong> Chapter 13. </strong></em>Developments in employee privacy rights among hospitality organizations: a progression to a dichotomy of ethical interpret</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 14:</strong></em> The effects of webpages on customer satisfaction: a restaurant case study</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 15: </strong></em>Exploration of the linkages between the gastronomy and heritage of Tainan city, Taiwan</p>\r\n<p>&bull; <em><strong>Chapter 16.</strong></em> Estimating the immediate effects on an unprecedented event of terrorism</p>\r\n<p><strong>Tổng quan:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Bộ s&aacute;ch &ldquo;Advances in Hospitality and Leisure (AHL)&rdquo; &nbsp;- được b&igrave;nh duyệt xuất bản hằng năm &nbsp;hiện đang t&igrave;m c&aacute;ch cung cấp những hiểu biết mới từ ho&agrave;ng loạt những c&ocirc;ng tr&igrave;nh điều tra khoa học li&ecirc;n quan đến c&aacute;c lĩnh vực thuộc kh&aacute;ch sạn, giải tr&iacute; v&agrave; du lịch c&ugrave;ng l&uacute;c mở ra diễn đ&agrave;n chuy&ecirc;n về học thuật nhằm khuyến kh&iacute;ch thảo luận về&nbsp; c&aacute;c vấn đề hiện tại v&agrave; c&aacute;c xu hướng đang nổi bật thật sự cần cho sự tiến bộ, to&agrave;n diện về l&yacute; thuyết cũng như thực tế theo quan điểm to&agrave;n cầu.</p>\r\n<p>Trong t&acirc;m ch&iacute;nh của loạt s&aacute;ch nhằm tiết lộ c&aacute;c phương ph&aacute;p s&aacute;ng tạo trong việc điều tra v&agrave; cũng để truyền cảm hứng tạo ra c&aacute;c chủ đề nghi&ecirc;n cứu mới &ndash; những chủ đề mang t&iacute;nh cấp thiết đ&atilde; bị l&atilde;ng qu&ecirc;n. AHL phấn đấu để chuy&ecirc;n v&agrave;o nhu cầu của cộng đồng &ndash; sẵn s&agrave;ng phổ biến c&aacute;c &yacute; tưởng, kh&aacute;i niệm v&agrave; c&aacute;c học thuyết từ&nbsp; nhu cầu nghi&ecirc;n cứu chuy&ecirc;n đề. Những đọc giả của loạt s&aacute;ch n&agrave;y sẽ c&oacute; được b&agrave;i tham khảo hữu &iacute;ch cho c&ocirc;ng tr&igrave;nh nghi&ecirc;n cứu, hay đề nghị những chủ đề khả thi cho c&ocirc;ng tr&igrave;nh nghi&ecirc;n cứu v&agrave; chắc chắn mang lại nhiều kiến thức chuy&ecirc;n ng&agrave;nh của bạn.</p>\r\n<p>Kể từ loạt s&aacute;ch đầu năm 2004, AHL đ&atilde; xuất bạn&nbsp; một loạt những ấn phẩm chuy&ecirc;n ng&agrave;nh gi&aacute; trị&nbsp; cả về kh&aacute;i niệm v&agrave; kinh nghiệm được đ&oacute;ng g&oacute;p bởi c&aacute;c học giả tr&ecirc;n khắp 14 quốc gia . C&aacute;c chủ đề&nbsp; nghi&ecirc;n cứu cũng dựa tr&ecirc;n c&aacute;c vấn đề như: h&agrave;nh vi người ti&ecirc;u d&ugrave;ng, c&aacute;c t&aacute;c động kinh tế, t&aacute;c động m&ocirc;i trường, quản l&yacute; nguồn nh&acirc;n lực, tiếp thị, thi&ecirc;n tai, chiến lược gi&aacute;, ph&aacute;t triển sản phẩm du lịch, quản l&yacute; rủi ro, chất lượng dịch vụ v&agrave; cả vấn đề khủng bố hiện nay.</p>', 'F2 JS2004', 'Joseph S. Chen', '2011-02-11 16:41:56', 'MTMzMzI4MTUzM19BZHZhbmNlcy1pbi1Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1hbmQtTGVpc3VyZS1Wb2w=.1.pdf', '892', '57', '0', '4.5', '14501', '2');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('36', 'Handout - Events & Logistics', '<p>Events &amp; Logistics Management</p>', '01', 'Jessica Mackie', '2011-02-11 04:51:45', 'MTI5NzM5OTkwNV93ZWVrXzRfbG9naXN0aWNz.pdf', '1136', '94', '0', '4.33333', '1166', '3');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('44', 'Hospitality Financial Management', '<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Hospitality Financial Management</strong> is an up-to-date introductory finance text written specifically for  those in hospitality and tourism. It uses hospitality examples to cover  concepts from a practical perspective, explaining and demonstrating the  importance of financial management in the hospitality industry.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The text covers such  important topics as an introduction to financial markets and  instruments, a review of financial statements, risk and return, time and  value of money, stock and bond valuation, capital budgeting, plus hotel  market studies/appraisals and capital structure of the firm.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><strong>Key Features:</strong> </span></span></span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">\r\n<li>Up-to-date hospitality examples </li>\r\n<li>Chapter exhibits connect chapter concepts with hospitality companies </li>\r\n<li>Practical applications </li>\r\n<li>Step-by-step guides to using financial calculators </li>\r\n<li>Capital budgeting project examples</li>\r\n</span></span></span> \r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Written in a clear and easy to understand format, <strong>Hospitality Financial Management</strong> is designed to equip readers with a basic knowledge of the financial management function in the hospitality industry.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Contents</strong></span> </span></span></span></p>\r\n<ol><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">\r\n<li>Introduction </li>\r\n<li>Financial Markets and Financial Instruments </li>\r\n<li>Review of Financial Statements and Selected Ratios </li>\r\n<li>The Relationship Between Risk and Return </li>\r\n<li>Time Value of Money </li>\r\n<li>Fixed-Income Securities: Bonds and Preferred Stock </li>\r\n<li>Common Stock </li>\r\n<li>Cost of Capital </li>\r\n<li>Introduction to Capital Budgeting and Cash Flow Estimation </li>\r\n<li>Capital Budgeting Decision Methods </li>\r\n<li>An Introduction to Hotel Valuation </li>\r\n<li>Capital Structure</li>\r\n</span></span></span></ol>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Glossary<br> Index</span></span></span></p>', '', 'by Robert Chatfield and Michael Dalbor', '2011-02-24 07:46:48', 'MTI5ODUzMzYwOF9ob3NwaXRhbGl0eS1maW5hbmNpYWwtbWFuYWdlbWVudA==.pdf', '964', '110', '0', '5', '1138', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('45', 'Dictionary of Travel, Tourism and Hospitality, Third Edition', '<p>The Dictionary Of Travel, Tourism And Hospitality defines and explains  mo re than 3000 terms and abbreviations in travel, tourism and  hospitality. It also lists key data for more than 200 countries. The  Dictionary Of Travel, Tourism And Hospitality covers business and emp  loyment terms, environmental issues, European integration, food and  catering, forms and types of tourism and recreation, and travel-related  illnesses. The Dictionary Of Travel, Touri sm And Hospitality is a  combination reference tool, manual and textbook. The Dictionary Of  Travel , Tourism And Hospitality is a useful reference work for travel  agents, travel guide wr iters, business travelers, and recreational  tourists.</p>', '', 'S. Medlik', '2011-02-24 08:01:31', 'MTI5ODUzNDQ5MV9EaWN0aW9uYXJ5LW9mLVRyYXZlbCwtVG91cmlzbSwtJi1Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eQ==.pdf', '1505', '268', '0', '4', '1142', '4');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('46', 'Hospitality Management Accounting', '<p>As the hospitality industry continues to grow and the business  environment become ever more competitive, it must become increasingly  profit and cost-conscious in order to maximize revenue and minimize  costs, all while maintaining the level of service necessary for a  successful operation. There is no other hospitality management  accounting book on the market that combines essential information,  illustrative examples, and useful problems and exercises. .</p>', '', 'Martin G. Jagels, Michael M. Coltman ', '2011-02-24 08:16:33', 'MTI5ODUzNTM5M19XaWxleS0tLUhvc3BpdGFsaXR5LU1hbmFnZW1lbnQtQWNjb3VudGluZw==.pdf', '1143', '63', '0', null, '1146', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('47', 'Marketing in Travel and Tourism', '<p>Now in its third edition, Marketing in Travel and  Tourism, explains the principles and practice of marketing as they are  increasingly being applied in the global travel and tourism industry.  Building on the success of previous editions, the authors have  completely revised the text to reflect the changes in the travel and  tourism industry in the 21st century.<br><br> International examples  and case studies drawn from recent practice in several countries are  used throughout the text. Case studies emphasising the role of ICT  include: Microburners, Travel Inn (budget hotels), RCI Europe, the  Balearic Islands, and ICT and the role of the Internet in international  NTO strategies.<br><br>With its comprehensive content and user friendly  style, Marketing in Travel and Tourism third edition takes the reader  from an initial definition of the subject matter through to the  application of marketing in the travel and tourism industry, discussing  crucial components such as planning strategy and the marketing mix,  making it an indispensable text for both students and practitioners  alike.</p>', '', 'Jackie R. Clarke, Victor T.C. Middleton', '2011-02-24 10:33:20', 'MTI5ODU0MzYwMF9NYXJrZXRpbmctaW4tVHJhdmVsLWFuZC1Ub3VyaXNt.pdf', '1712', '284', '0', '5', '1154', '2');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('48', 'Hospitality Law Managing Legal Issues in the Hospitality Indust', '<p>Reliable advice to help hospitality managers prevent legal problems and avoid litigation.<br> Is an unhappy restaurant guest legally entitled to a refund for food she  ate? Is a hotel required to replace money that a guest claims was taken  from his room? Can a hospital food and beverage director legally accept  a holiday gift from a vendor without threatening her employment status?<br> Hospitality Law, Second Edition provides readers with answers to these  questions and more. Packed with interactive exercises as well as  up-to-date legal information specific to the hospitality industry,  Hospitality Law benefits students by emphasizing preventive legal  management and effective decision-making.<br> This Second Edition gives students and managers background on safety and  security requirements, disputes with customers, hiring and firing  employees, liabilities associated with serving alcohol, and much more,  including: New coverage of legal issues in travel and tourism, including  those associated with transportation, travel agents, tour operators,  gaming, mixed-use, and timeshare properties Newly added real-world legal  case summaries that illustrate the practical application of hospitality  laws in actual hospitality operations. Each case summary features a  \"Message to Management\" that gives the reader a clear explanation of the  impact of the decision on best practices, as well as preventative  measures managers can take to limit exposure New coverage of legal  issues related to amusement parks and the Internet booking phenomenon  New \"International Snapshots\" offering insights from practicing  attorneys and other professionals regarding differences between U.S. and  international laws related to hospitality Updated Web exercises and  guidance for researching on the Internet<br> Encouraging readers to think critically about legal concepts related to  hospitality, Hospitality Law, Second Edition is an indispensable part of  every hospitality manager\'s education.</p>', '', 'Stephen Barth, David K. Hayes ', '2011-02-24 10:34:45', 'MTI5ODU0MzY4NV9Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1MYXctTWFuYWdpbmctTGVnYWwtSXNzdWVzLWluLXRoZS1Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1JbmR1c3RyeQ==.pdf', '590', '11', '250', null, '1170', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('49', 'Hotel Front Office Management. 3rd edition', '<p>Hotel Front Office Management uses a human resources approach to cover  the unique management and operational challenges in the front offices of  todays hotels and lodging facilities. This Third Edition continues its  emphasis on applying theory and management strategies, as well as  providing new material on technologys role in the modernized front  office. <br><br>Material is logically presented in the order of  operations: an overview of lodging hospitality, a tour of the front  office, a review of the guest cycle, and an analysis of guest services.  Practical features of this new edition include: <br><br>A new chapter on property management systems to address industry-wide changes<br><br>Practical case study problems in each chapter<br><br>Commentaries from hotel front office managers, general managers, and other department managers<br><br>Articles on the international hotel work force<br><br>Additional case studies for applying theory and developing problem-solving strategies<br><br>Hotel  Front Office Management, Third Edition, is an invaluable book for those  interested in learning more about the hotels front office.</p>', '', 'James A. Bardi', '2011-02-24 10:59:50', 'MTI5ODU0NTE5MF9K.A.Bardi - Hotel Front Office Management. 3rd edition.pdf', '1732', '0', '0', '3.66667', '1174', '3');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('50', 'Timeshare Resort Operations', '<p><strong>Overview</strong></p>\r\n<p>The timeshare industry is a new but fast developing business activityacross the world. Timeshare properties are now found in over 95 countriesand on all of the world&rsquo;s continents. In the last couple of decades, timesharebusiness activities have become increasingly branded as large hotel,resort, and leisure attraction developers have added timeshare offers totheir portfolio of accommodation provision. The entry of large corporate,branded, global players has done much to increase the professionalismof timeshare operations and management. It is against this culture ofincreasing professionalism that this book emerged. It is intended as text tosupport management programs at undergraduate and postgraduate levelsin higher education, and professional management development programsdelivered in industry for practitioners.</p>', '', 'Randall Upchurch, Conrad Lashley', '2011-03-10 03:29:54', 'MTI5OTcyNzc5NF9UaW1lc2hhcmUtUmVzb3J0LU9wZXJhdGlvbnMtZ1BH.pdf', '1178', '38', '0', '5', '1322', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('51', 'Hotel Design Magazine Dec 2008', '<p>Hotel Design celebrates the design excellence of hotels, resorts, lodges and destination spas. Vivid photography, creative layouts and descriptive writing help present to the reader a broad focus on the new styles and fashion trends emerging in furniture, fixtures and the lodging spaces that provide a foundation for creativity. Hotel Design aims to be the source of inspiration for the individuals who help make it happen.</p>', '', 'Hotel Network Publication', '2011-03-10 05:59:44', 'MTI5OTczNjc4NF9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tRGVjZW1iZXItMjAwOA==.pdf', '757', '29', '0', '5', '1332', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('52', 'Principles of Hotel Management', '<p>The classical theorists have developed certain principles oforganisations for the guidance of managers and executives andthey claim them as fundamental, essential, inevitable anduniversal. Though divergence of views exists, there is aconsiderable degree of unanimity on these principles. Fayol wasthe first to give principles of administration. He developed acomprehensive list of fourteen principles: (i) division of work;(ii) authority and responsibility; (iii) discipline; (iv) unity ofcommand; (v) unity of direction; (vi) subordination of individualinterests to general interests; (vii) fair remuneration; (viii) equityand a sense of justice; (ix) stability; (x) initiative; and (xi) teamworkspirit. These principles are more or less have a considerabledegree of unanimity and some of these principles are stillapplied in organisations.</p>', '', 'V. Prakesh Kainthola', '2011-03-10 07:23:46', 'MTI5OTc0MTgyNl84MTIyNDE0MTkyLUhvdGVsQQ==.pdf', '1316', '241', '0', '4.25', '1336', '4');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('53', 'Hotel Design Magazine Jan 2010', '<p>I&rsquo;m going to stay positive in 2010 and say thatour industry is on the upswing. But I thinkit&rsquo;s also instructive to look back a little andsee how the financial difficulties have beentransformative for the design industry.Todd Lundgren, VP at RTKL Associates, saysthe economic downturn generally has led to agreater level of economy and efficiency&mdash;peoplewant to get more and pay for less. As a result, thechallenge for designers is providing that &lsquo;more&rsquo; increative, flexible and efficient ways.</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:17:52', 'MTMwMDAxMTQ3Ml9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tSmFuLUZlYi0yMDEw.pdf', '397', '12', '0', null, '1342', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('54', 'Hotel Design Magazine Mar 2010', '<p>D.B. Kim stands out in a room. Theaward-winning designer has a certainpresence to begin with, but his short,stylish mohawk ensures he won&rsquo;t beoverlooked. I had the chance to chat with him atthe inaugural InspireDesign show in Las Vegasabout where design is headed.Guestroom design is going</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:21:56', 'MTMwMDAxMTcxNl9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tTWFyLTIwMTA=.pdf', '242', '6', '0', null, '1346', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('55', 'Hotel Design Magazine Apr 2010', '<p>When was the last time you thoughtabout lighting? If you&rsquo;re likemost, it was probably when younoticed a bad example of it&mdash;aguestroom with dim fixtures or a lobby withspotlights overpowering an otherwise elegantpiece of artwork. But done correctly, lightingwill accentuate your designs, not call attention toitself.&ldquo;Not only are spaces that are over-lit distractingand uncomfortable, but they also drain aton of unnecessary energy,&rdquo; says Al Near, SVPof sales and marketing for USA Illumination.&ldquo;Conversely, if energy savings is too much a focalpoint, then space can tend to be under-lit &hellip; thenattempts to create lighting effects or drama mayfall flat.&rdquo;According</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:26:12', 'MTMwMDAxMTk3Ml9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tQXByLTIwMTA=.pdf', '217', '14', '0', null, '1350', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('56', 'Hotel Design Magazine May 2010', '<p>I&rsquo;m not sure what it is about China, but theword is a loaded term in some industries.Where furniture is concerned, I thinkmost designers have a good concept ofwhat is possible from Chinese manufacturers,but there still is a lot of misinformation&mdash;andmisunderstanding&mdash;rampant among hoteliers.The million-dollar question is, of course,quality. In some manufacturing areas, &ldquo;made inChina&rdquo; is practically synonymous with poorlybuilt products. But in our industry,</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:32:26', 'MTMwMDAxMjM0Nl9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tTWF5LTIwMTA=.pdf', '246', '12', '0', null, '1354', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('57', 'Hotel Design Magazine Jun 2010', '<p>Last month I had the opportunityto visit the new Home2 Suites byHilton brand&rsquo;s &ldquo;Oasis&rdquo; lobby andguestrooms. The experience wasespecially interesting, given that the firstproperty, slated for Fayetteville, N.C., will notopen until later this year.I was at Hilton&rsquo;s corporate offices in Memphis,where the brand has built out the Oasislobby inside one of their buildings, allowingfranchisees, investors and employees to reallytouch and see&mdash;and, of course, tweak&mdash;whatpreviously had been seen only in renderings. Afew miles away at the Shady Grove HamptonInn, Hilton has dedicated a cluster of fifth-floorrooms for several of its brands</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:36:46', 'MTMwMDAxMjYwNl9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tSnVuZS0yMDEw.pdf', '581', '19', '0', '5', '1358', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('58', 'Hotel Design Magazine Jul 2010', '<p>We&rsquo;ve heard countlesstimes in the lastfew months thatrenovations are on the rise.That message was echoedrecently both at HD Expo andthe NYU International HospitalityIndustry InvestmentConference.I saw many of you at therenovation panel at NYU titled,&ldquo;Band-aids vs. Facelifts.&rdquo;The message there was loudand clear: The places to investin for &lsquo;band-aid renovations&rsquo; areflooring, bedding and artwork.</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:43:57', 'MTMwMDAxMzAzN19Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tSnVsLVNlcC0yMDEw.pdf', '308', '13', '0', null, '1362', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('59', 'Hotel Design Magazine Sep 2010', '<p>Ever since Barcelona, I&rsquo;ve been engrossed by design.Maybe it was the ubiquity of Gaud&iacute;, but everybuilding in the Spanish city, every landscaped park,looked like it had been spun by a master designer.That was the case when I checked into W Barcelona, which,because it sits on the outskirts of what one might describe asthe hub of the city, looks like a glimmering beacon. And itdoes attract&mdash;particularly those travelers who have an eye forhaute design. The architect of the hotel, Ricardo Bofill, craftedthe exterior to look like a sail (thankfully, because my limitedSpanish made it difficult to explain to our taxi driver where weneeded to go&mdash;that was until he exclaimed, &ldquo;Oh, vela!&rdquo;). Theall-glass shell gives way to an array of amenities and whimsicaltouches inside. W is on the cutting edge when it comes tobathroom design, eschewing the tub and ramping up theshower experience. Fret not: those who still love taking a bathcan do so in the stand-alone tub that resides in the living room.</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 10:57:35', 'MTMwMDAxMzg1NV9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tU2VwLTIwMTA=.pdf', '1351', '40', '0', null, '1366', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('60', 'Hotel Design Magazine Oct 2010', '<p>Like anyone else, when I walk into anew hotel, the first thing I do is takean inventory of my surroundings.I look up at the lighting on theceiling, down at the floor and left and right forhow the entrance area is decked out. This sametype of exercise happens once again after I findmy way into my room.Point being, aesthetics carry a lot of weightin the overall hospitality experience. If youdon&rsquo;t believe me, it&rsquo;s actually been proven. In1999, Joseph Pine and James Gilmore penneda seminal article entitled &ldquo;Welcome to theExperience Economy,&rdquo; which set out a visionfor a new economic era where consumers arein search of memorable experiences. It statedthat there are four types of consumer experiences:entertainment, educational, escapist andesthetic (the four Es). Soon after, many researcherslooked to apply Pine&rsquo;s and Gilmore&rsquo;smodel to actual industries, including hotels.</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 11:00:10', 'MTMwMDAxNDAxMF9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tT2N0LTIwMTA=.pdf', '1207', '29', '0', '4', '1370', '2');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('61', 'Hotel Design Magazine Dec 2010', '<p>As we all know, business in this industry&mdash;and all industries, for that matter&mdash;isbased on relationships and friendships.This holiday, I am thankful for the gift ofthe hotel industry friendships.I was reminded of this when our company hosted atable at the AH&amp;LA Inaugural Dinner that was held duringthe IHMR show, in New York, on November 14.I know many ofthe hoteliers whoread our magazineare probablyalready members ofAH&amp;LA (AmericanHotel &amp; LodgingAssociation),but I encourageour vendors, ourdesigners and purchasingcompanyexecutives to alsojoin this fantasticorganization.For years, I</p>', '', 'A Hotel World Network Publication', '2011-03-13 11:10:35', 'MTMwMDAxNDYzNV9Ib3RlbC1EZXNpZ24tRGVjLTIwMTA=.pdf', '1447', '118', '0', '3.33333', '1374', '3');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('62', 'Food & Nutrition', '<p>The importance of diet to health, especially in the prevention and cure of illness, is slowly becoming apparent. I endeavour to provide you with more than the basic, and usually inaccurate information on diet and nutrition. So whether you are a registered dietitian and want to brush up on the immense amount of information, or whether you just want to find out, for the first time what you should be eating, then this site is for you.</p>', '', 'Don Ross', '2011-09-16 18:23:02', 'MTMxNjE5NzM4Ml9Gb29kLSYtTnV0aXRpb24=.pdf', '1052', '13', '110', '5', '4542', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('63', 'Economics of Hotel Management', '<p>The field of economics encompasses the study of the entire economic system &mdash; both at the micro and macro level. Hotel economics is one such area where the subject matter of economics has gained its growth in obtaining for the hotel industry needed aspects, right from its initiation, establishment, and growth. The hotel industry though considered to be a service sector has proved its might in different dimensions &mdash; providing employment, revenue to the government and also acting as a promoter of culture by developing the most vital industry which is tourism. Tourism has emerged as a most instrumental phenomenon in the economic and social development of the society. It also acts as a subsidiary in providing accommodation to the tourist who visit the country &mdash; by providing the most luxurious accommodation to the one like the motel where basic necessities are provided even to a poor tourist. It is seen that the industry as a whole generates not only a sizeable percentage of employment but also contributes to the GNP of a country. The importance of this field has grown over the years leading many institutes to provide education in this field.</p>', '', 'M.A. Sheela', '2011-09-16 18:27:15', 'MTMxNjE5NzYzNV9FY29ub21pY3Mtb2YtSG90ZWwtTWFuYWdlbWVudA==.pdf', '1439', '25', '120', '4', '4546', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('64', 'Accounting and Financial Management developments in the interna', '<p>The main purpose of this book is to present new and interesting<br>research and developments in the field of accounting and financial<br>management as they relate to the work of managing enterprises<br>and organizations in the international hospitality industry.<br>Although the focus is on hotels, the content can readily be interpreted<br>in a broader context. Many hospitality organizations contain<br>hotel services components such as the provision of rooms,<br>food and beverage facilities and, therefore, the examples and illustrations<br>can be related to restaurants, licensed house management,<br>hospital and university services, clubs and so on.<br>The content comprises state-of-the-art contributions from a<br>wide range of academics and practitioners engaged in hospitality<br>activities around the globe including researchers, university lecturers,<br>practising accountants, professional consultants and senior<br>managers and executives associated with the international<br>hospitality industry in the UK and abroad. The material is drawn<br>from their work and experience and relates directly to the management<br>of hospitality undertakings.</p>', 'C1 PM 2006', 'Peter Harris & Marco Mongiello', '2012-02-23 04:36:46', 'MTMyOTk3MTgwNl9BY2NvdW50aW5nLWFuZC1GaW5hbmNpYWwtTWFuYWdlbWVudC1kZXZlbG9wbWVudHMtaW4tdGhlLWludGVybmF0aW9uYWwtaG9zcGl0YWxpdHktaW5kdXN0cnk=.pdf', '385', '1', '300', '5', '25440', '1');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('65', 'Culinary Taste - Consumer Behaviour in the International Restau', '<p>Overview</p>\r\n<p>Culinary Taste: Consumer Behaviour in the International Restaurant Sector looks at the factors that influence our culinary tastes and dining behaviour, illustrating how they can translate into successful business in industry.<br>With a foreword from Prue Leith, restaurateur, author, teacher, and prolific cookery writer and novelist, and a list of well-known and respected international contributors from the UK, France, Australia and Hong Kong, this text discusses the issues involved from a multitude of angles. <br>* Provides wide-ranging insight into the nature of culinary taste as expressed in commercial restaurant settings<br>* Evaluates the influence on culinary taste of a variety of factors such as: social class, gender, health awareness, marketing and geography<br>* Considers the importance of understanding these issues for business management and for success in the hospitality industry today</p>\r\n<p><strong>Table of Contents</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. The social construction of taste - 2. The postmodern palate: dining out in the individualized era - 3. Taste and space: eating out in the city today - 4. Chic cuisine: the impact of fashion on food - 5. The shock of the new: a sociology of nouvelle cuisine - 6. Contemporary lifestyles: the case of wine - 7. Shaping culinary taste: the influence of commercial operators (We are what we eat, or what we are persuaded to eat?) - 8. Gender and culinary taste - 9. Developing a taste for health - 10. My most memorable meal ever! Hospitality as an emotional experience</p>', 'D1 DS 2004', 'Donald Sloan', '2012-02-23 05:07:16', 'MTMyOTk3MzYzNl9DdWxpbmFyeS1UYXN0ZS0tLUNvbnN1bWVyLUJlaGF2aW91ci1pbi10aGUtSW50ZXJuYXRpb25hbC1SZXN0YXVyYW50LVNlY3Rvci0oSG9zcGl0YWxpdHktLS1MZWlzdXJlLWFuZC1Ub3VyaXNtKQ==.pdf', '414', '7', '200', '4', '15388', '3');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('66', 'Hospitality Law - Managing Legal Issues in the Hospitality Indu', '<p>This textbook was written to help teach hospitality students what they need to<br>know to manage a facility legally, safely, and securely.<br>In the day-to-day operation of a hospitality facility, it is the manager, not the<br>company attorney, who will most influence the legal position of the operation. Rarely<br>will you find a hospitality manager who is also a licensed attorney. However, professional<br>hospitality managers (and, by extension, their staffs) make decisions every<br>day based on their own interpretation of the law. The quality of these decisions will<br>ultimately determine whether lawyers and the expense of fees, trials, and potential<br>judgments may become necessary. A few examples will help illustrate this fact.</p>', 'J1 SB 2009', 'Stephen Barth', '2012-02-23 05:25:03', 'MTMyOTk3NDcwM19Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1MYXctLS1NYW5hZ2luZy1MZWdhbC1Jc3N1ZXMtaW4tdGhlLUhvc3BpdGFsaXR5LUluZHVzdHJ5LS0tM3JkLUVkaXRpb24=.pdf', '448', '0', '200', '5', '25436', '2');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('67', 'Advances in Culture, Tourism and Hospitality Research Vol.1', '<p>Advances in Culture, Tourism, and Hospitality Research (ACTHR) is a newbook series that provides a forum for scholarly contributions offering bothbroad and deep reports of progress in theory, research, and practice inrelating the fields of culture, tourism and hospitality. ACTHR welcomeslong papers that delve deeply into antecedents, behaviors, and consequencesof topics related to culture, tourism, and hospitality.Similar to issues of scholarly journals, paper submissions to ACTHR aredouble-blind reviewed &ndash; members of the ACTHR Editorial Board provideextensive suggestions to authors for revising submissions during the reviewprocess. Unlike most journals, the ACTHR has no page limits; possibly oneor two lengthy papers will constitute an entire future volume in this series.The aim is to encourage authors to ponder and report on how their paperscontribute to building an interdisciplinary theory of human behaviorbeyond the borders of psychology, sociology, marketing, management,tourism, geography, hospitality, and other fields in the behavioral sciences.This preface champions the view that weak cultural and psychological tiesboth stimulate and inhibit tourism and hospitality behavior. Many of theseties are held unconsciously by consumers, and some ties may be retrievableautomatically when thinking about a tourism-related activity. In most casesthe presence of any one weak tie is necessary, but not sufficient to result in aspecific stream of tourism behavior; the conjunctive presence of three ormore antecedent events are observable in different streams of behaviorrelating to tourism and hospitality experiences.xi</p>', '', 'Arch G. Woodside', '2012-03-12 03:19:43', 'MTMzMTUyMjM4M19BZHZhbmNlcy1pbi1DdWx0dXJlLC1Ub3VyaXNtLWFuZC1Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1SZXNlYXJjaC1Wb2w=.1.pdf', '96', '2', '200', null, '13153', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('68', 'Advances in Culture, Tourism and Hospitality Research Vol.2', '<p>Volume 2 contributes to the general theme of this Advances series by offeringoriginal, eclectic theories and field studies that focus on culture, tourism,and hospitality research. Volume 2 includes chapters without lengthrestrictions, giving authors the opportunity to provide more nuancedexplorations of theory, method, and their findings, and so create articles thatsharpen and deepen thinking to a greater extent than is usually possible injournal-length articles. Unlike handbooks of original essays, this Advancesseries aims to include chapters on topics and coverage heretofore missingfrom the literature, but that nevertheless build on prior scholarlycontributions. Consequently, the primary objective for Volume 2 is toprovide must-read chapters unavailable from other sources &ndash; a wellspringproviding exceptional insights and tools for applied researchers and scholarsfocusing on culture, tourism, and hospitality.</p>', '', 'Arch G. Woodside', '2012-03-12 03:25:52', 'MTMzMTUyMjc1Ml9BZHZhbmNlcy1pbi1DdWx0dXJlLC1Ub3VyaXNtLWFuZC1Ib3NwaXRhbGl0eS1SZXNlYXJjaC1Wb2w=.2.pdf', '91', '2', '200', null, '13157', '0');
INSERT INTO `engine4_library_books` VALUES ('69', 'Adventure Tourism ', '<p><strong>Overview</strong></p>\r\n<p>Adventure tourism is a new and rapidly growing area, both in practice and in academic interest, as outdoor recreation has become increasingly commercialized. This volume provides a comprehensive introduction and a state-of-the-art review of adventure tourism from both theoretical and practical perspectives. It includes technical analyses of over 100 real-life retail adventure tourism products from around the globe, in a wide variety of outdoor activity sectors. Adventure Tourism will appeal to those studying tourism, leisure, recreation and adventure tourism management and also to practitioners in the adventure tourism industry.</p>\r\n<p><strong>About the Author</strong></p>\r\n<p>Professor Raft Buckley is hold as Director and Chair, International Centre for Ecotourism Research<br>He has worked&nbsp; in some fields: Field ecologist, 30 years. EIA, environmental management, audit and monitoring, 20 years. Project management, 20 years. Tourism and environment, 15 years.<br>And the recent research about environmental impacts of tourism. Monitoring and management of visitors and natural resources in national parks. Environmental guidelines for adventure tourism and recreation. Triple-bottom-line reporting for ecotourism. Ecolabelling in tourism. Effectiveness of education as a minimal-impact management tool.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Table of Contents</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Chap. 1</em> Introduction &ndash; <em>Chap. 2 </em>Adverture Recreation Research &ndash; <em>Chap. 3</em> Case Study Approach, River Journeys &ndash; <em>Chap. 4</em> Whitewater Kayaking &ndash; <em>Chap. 5</em> Whitewater Rafting &ndash; <em>Chap. 6</em> Seakayaking &ndash; <em>Chap. 7</em> Sailing &ndash; <em>Chap.8 </em>Expedition Cruises &ndash; <em>Chap.9</em> Diving &ndash; <em>Chap. 10 </em>Sur.ng &ndash; <em>Chap. 11</em> Heliski and Snowboard &ndash; <em>Chap.12</em> Cross-country Skiing &ndash; <em>Chap. 13</em> Ice Climbing &ndash; <em>Chap. 14</em> Mountaineering &ndash;<em> Chap. 15 </em>Hiking and Bushwalking &ndash; <em>Chap.16</em> Horse Riding &ndash; Chap. 17 Mountain Biking &ndash; Chap. 18 Off-road Safaris &ndash; <em>Chap.19</em> Wildlife &ndash; <em>Chap. 20</em> Aerial Adventures &ndash; <em>Chap. 21</em> Other Sectors and Issues &ndash; <em>Chap. 22</em> Adventure Destinations &ndash; <em>Chap. 23</em> World Adventure Capital &ndash; <em>Chap. 24 </em>Cross-case Analyses &ndash; <em>Chap. 25</em> Product Patterns &ndash; <em>Chap. 26 </em>Conclusions</p>\r\n<p><strong>Tổng quan</strong></p>\r\n<p>Du lịch mạo hiểm l&agrave; một trong những linh vực mới v&agrave; ph&aacute;t triển với tốc độ cao, cả về t&iacute;nh thương mại thực tế v&agrave; học thuật, giờ đ&acirc;y h&igrave;nh thức giải tr&iacute; ngo&agrave;i trời đang ng&agrave;y c&agrave;ng thương mại h&oacute;a nhanh hơn. Quyển s&aacute;ch cho ch&uacute;ng ta&nbsp; một giới thiệu tổng qu&aacute;t v&agrave; cập nhật những phi&ecirc;n bản mới nhất về du lịch mạo hiểm từ cả hai quan điểm về l&yacute; luận v&agrave; thực tiễn. Bao gồm những ph&acirc;n t&iacute;ch chuy&ecirc;n về kỹ thuật của hơn 100 sản phẩm du lịch mạo hiểm từ khắp nơi tr&ecirc;n thế giới, trong lĩnh vực hoạt động giải tr&iacute; ngo&agrave;i trời. Du lịch mạo hiểm trong tương lai sẽ thu h&uacute;t nhiều về vấn đề nghi&ecirc;n cứu, quản l&yacute; v&agrave; c&aacute;c học vi&ecirc;n gia nhập v&agrave;o loại h&igrave;nh du lịch mới n&agrave;y &ndash; du lịch mạo hiểm</p>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" class=\"mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow: hidden;\"><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o:OfficeDocumentSettings> <o:AllowPNG> </o:OfficeDocumentSettings> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:TrackMoves> <w:TrackFormatting> <w:PunctuationKerning> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:Sav